<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLAN MALAMUD: NOTES ON A SCORECARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN MALAMUD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 That was some Garden party. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 From the San Jose Sharks' seven-game shocker over the Detroit Red Wings in the 
first round to the New York Rangers' seven-game sweat over the Vancouver 
Canucks in the championship series, the Stanley Cup playoffs couldn't have been 
better. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 A lot of crazy things happened the last couple of months, but the Cup is where 
it belongs, in the possession of the best and most-deserving team. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 What worked for Eric Karros in the Texas League four years ago is doing the 
job for him now in the National League. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Karros, one of the hottest hitters in baseball, has returned to the open 
stance he used when he batted .352 for the Dodgers' double-A farm club at San 
Antonio. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "For some reason, I got away from it," said Karros, the 1992 National League 
rookie of the year. "I went back to it a couple of weeks ago. I'm seeing the 
ball a lot better now." . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Karros has a reputation for being a better second-half than first-half hitter. 
. . .  
</P>
<P>
 "We'll have to see what happens this year," he said. "That is, if there is a 
second half." . . .  
</P>
<P>
 When he is joined by second baseman Garey Ingram, shortstop Jose Offerman and 
third baseman Tim Wallach, first baseman Karros is the only member of the 
Dodger infield who didn't hit a home run in his first major league at-bat. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 Little did anyone suspect that Ryne Sandberg's last day in the Chicago lineup 
might have been Friday, when he went 0 for 4 against Kevin Gross during the 
Cubs' 2-1 loss to the Dodgers at Wrigley Field. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "I was shocked," Dodger Manager Tom Lasorda said after hearing of Sandberg's 
retirement announcement. "His manager said he was putting too much pressure on 
himself, but nobody had any idea about him quitting. I had the pleasure of 
managing him in All-Star games. He was a terrific player and a good guy." . . . 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Reliever Tim Fortugno of the Cincinnati Reds, then 30, was the Angels' oldest 
rookie ever in 1990 and is best remembered for giving up hit No. 3,000 to 
George Brett and then picking him off first base. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Fortugno returned to the minors with Ottawa in 1993, was released by the 
Seattle Mariners after spending the spring in their minor league camp, pitched 
14 games with the Reds' Chattanooga farm club and was called up May 13 after 
Tom Browning was injured. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 He is a graduate of Southern California College, whose pitching staff this 
year included Ila Borders. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 How odd that Bret Saberhagen is 7-3 in an even-numbered year. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The New York Mets' right-hander was 39-53 in even-numbered years before this 
one and never had a winning record in any of them. He is 81-37 and never has 
had a losing record in odd-numbered years. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Every time I see Wrigley Field in Chicago, I'm reminded of old Wrigley Field 
in L.A., which was a gem of a minor league park before housing the Angels 
during their first American League season of 1961. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 This Wrigley, at 42nd and Avalon, always had lights and was the scene of 
several major fights, including Joe Louis-Jack Roper, Floyd Patterson-Roy 
Harris, Sugar Ray Robinson-Bobo Olson and Carmen Basilio-Art Aragon. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 That Jose Canseco-Ken Griffey Jr. power show Monday in Texas was simply 
marvelous, juiced-up ball or no. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 I prefer the NHL's 2-2-1-1-1 format in the finals to the NBA's 2-3-2, which 
was implemented several years ago so teams wouldn't have to travel so much. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 It seems more fair to both sides, although the World Series also is contested 
under the NBA format. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Centers Hakeem Olajuwon and Patrick Ewing are the stars, but the three-point 
shooters might decide the NBA finals. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 In 1923, it took Gene Sarazen 194 holes to win the PGA Championship under a 
match-play format at Pelham Manor, N.Y. . . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Despite being out of action for three months after a skiing accident, Phil 
Mickelson, 24, has improved to seventh in the U.S. Ryder Cup team standings. . 
. .  
</P>
<P>
 UCLA guard Tyus Edney has been invited to try out for the U.S. Goodwill Games 
team, coached by USC's George Raveling, at the UC Irvine training camp that 
begins July 4. Bruin Ed O'Bannon has withdrawn because of a summer school 
commitment. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The women's version of the Say No Classic will tip off Saturday at 10 a.m. at 
the North Gym at USC. Twelve teams of current and former college basketball 
players will participate in the six-week tournament. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 It's never too early to start thinking about college football. The Sporting 
News' preseason magazine has UCLA ranked 14th and USC 19th nationally. Bruin 
J.J. Stokes is rated the best wide receiver and Bjorn Merten the second-best 
kicker. Trojan Rob Johnson is the No. 2 quarterback behind Stanford's Steve 
Stenstrom, and Tony Boselli is the No. 5 offensive tackle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
