<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV RATINGS; NBC WINS THE WEEK, BUT ABC'S 'GRACE' IS NO. 1 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE MARGULIES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The National Basketball Assn. championships sent NBC's ratings jumping last 
week, giving the peacock network its first win in the weekly prime-time 
competition since it televised the Super Bowl in January. Ratings released 
Tuesday by the A.C. Nielsen Co. showed two of the New York-Houston games 
finishing among the week's Top 10. 
</P>
<P>
 But the No. 1 show of the week was ABC's "Grace Under Fire," starring Brett 
Butler. It was seen in about 15.7 million homes. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides basketball, newsmagazines also did very well last week as viewers 
sought something other than reruns. "60 Minutes," "Turning Point," "20/20," 
"Dateline NBC" and "48 Hours" all finished in the Top 20. 
</P>
<P>
 What didn't fare well was the Tony Awards on Sunday night. The CBS telecast 
attracted only 14% of the available viewers and finished 49th among the week's 
91 prime-time network programs. Ratings for the salute to Broadway's best plays 
and performers were down about 12% from last year. Southland Ratings 
</P>
<P>
 Here are A. C. Nielsen's Top 10 prime-time programs in the Los Angeles area 
during the same week. Each rating point equals 50,064 households. 
