<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: VAN NUYS; MAN GIVEN 
PROBATION FOR ENCOURAGING SUICIDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Tujunga man convicted of encouraging his despondent roommate to commit 
suicide was sentenced to four years probation Tuesday by a judge who called the 
episode a "tragic case." 
</P>
<P>
 Alex Coventry, 44, who had been found guilty of violating California's rarely 
used, 121-year-old assisted suicide law, was also ordered by Van Nuys Superior 
Court Judge Ronald S. Coen to perform 500 hours of community service.Coventry 
gave his roommate a loaded shotgun last July and told him to "just do it." 
</P>
<P>
 "I am convinced that even the most diligent of advocates for assisted suicide 
for purposes of mercy would condemn the actions of the defendant," Coen said at 
the sentencing.  
</P>
<P>
 The judge made a "strong recommendation" that Coventry do his community 
service "in the area of suicide prevention," such as a suicide hot line. 
</P>
<P>
 Coventry was found guilty of the felony charge in the suicide of Leonard 
Medina, a 42-year-old unemployed man who shared a Tujunga apartment with 
Coventry and Linda McDowell, Coventry's girlfriend. Medina and McDowell had 
been drinking heavily most of the day of the suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
