<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: NEWPORT BEACH; POLICE, ARTS CUTBACKS CRITICIZED AT HEARING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city's 1994-95 fiscal year budget, which calls for reductions in police 
and arts funding, was criticized at a public hearing this week. 
</P>
<P>
 The $60-million general fund budget calls for a variety of cutbacks designed 
to close a $3-million gap.The City Council is expected to take a final vote on 
the budget June 27. 
</P>
<P>
 City Manager Kevin J. Murphy's budget calls for eliminating about 30 jobs, 
including eight in the Police Department. Most of the eight jobs are vacant, so 
no one in the department will be laid off. 
</P>
<P>
 The vacancies have reduced the number of patrol officers. Murphy said the 
budget would make those staffing reductions permanent. 
</P>
<P>
 At the hearing Monday, some residents opposed the police cuts, saying the city 
should increase funding to the department as a way of fighting crime. 
</P>
<P>
 The budget also calls for cuts in arts funding, from $44,000 to $25,000. Two 
years ago, the city spent $51,000 on arts, mostly in the form of grants to 
various organizations and artists. 
</P>
<P>
 On May 1, the city laid off six workers, including two in the Fire Department. 
Over the last three years, Newport Beach has cut a total of 90 positions, 22 of 
those from the Police Department. SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</TEXT>
