<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: AUTOMOBILES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by John O'Dell, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ontario Parts Center: Nearly 18 months after announcing the project, Toyota 
Motor Sales U.S.A. finally has broken ground on a $75-million North American 
parts center in Ontario. The 760,000-square-foot facility is being built by 
Irvine general contractor Snyder Langston. 
</P>
<P>
 Toyota officials say they will hire almost 400 people to staff the huge 
facility, which will take over the company's U.S. parts-handling chores, now 
done in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
 Toyota thinks so much of the project, one of the largest construction jobs in 
Southern California in years, that corporate chairman T. Toyoda flew in from 
Japan to attend Monday's groundbreaking ceremonies. Other dignitaries included 
Gov. Pete Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
 Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. is headquartered in Torrance, and the new parts 
center is in Riverside County. But the car maker's operations cover the entire 
Southern California basin. Calty, Toyota's U.S. research and design center, is 
in Newport Beach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
