<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: AUTOMOBILES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by John O'Dell, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 4WD Sports Utes: Most car dealers practice diversification -- sell trucks, 
imports, domestics, entry-level and luxury cars and you have something for 
everyone. 
</P>
<P>
 But a counter-cyclical car lot opens its doors today in Mission Viejo. 
</P>
<P>
 Land Rover Mission Viejo is among the first in a string of centers the British 
truck company plans for the United States. The only new vehicles to be sold 
there are four-wheel-drive Land Rovers: the new Discovery model, the Defender 
90 and the Range Rover. 
</P>
<P>
 Dealer Ken McGraw, former vice president of marketing for Land Rover North 
America, will offer a variety of makes in his used car section, but only of the 
four-wheel-drive sports utility variety: Explorers, Blazers, Jeeps, Monteros, 
Troopers, Rodeos, Pathfinders and the like. 
</P>
<P>
 Trucks for personal rather than business use are the best-selling vehicles in 
the nation, and 4WD sports utes, as fans call them, are the hottest branch on 
the truck family tree. McGraw said his goal is to make the dealership a must 
stop for every four-wheel-drive shopper in Orange County, even if they're not 
in the market for one of Land Rover's $28,000-and-up models. 
</P>
</TEXT>
